Smart Biometric Attendance System using ESP32
Overview

This project is a complete industrial-grade biometric attendance management system developed using the ESP32 microcontroller. The system combines biometric authentication, real-time clock synchronization, local and cloud-based data storage, automatic Wi-Fi management, and self-diagnostic capabilities to create a reliable and scalable attendance solution.

Unlike traditional attendance systems that depend entirely on internet connectivity or external servers, this device is designed to operate autonomously. Attendance data is securely stored both in onboard flash memory and on an SD card, ensuring that no records are lost even during network failures, power interruptions, or server downtime. When connectivity becomes available, the system automatically synchronizes pending attendance records to the cloud.

The project demonstrates the integration of embedded systems, IoT technologies, cloud services, real-time processing, and industrial reliability concepts into a single device.

Key Features
Biometric Authentication

The system uses an AS608 fingerprint sensor to identify users accurately and securely. Each employee or student is registered using a fingerprint template stored within the sensor's internal memory. During attendance marking, fingerprints are matched locally, eliminating the need for internet connectivity during authentication.

Real-Time Attendance Logging

Every attendance entry is timestamped using a DS3231 Real-Time Clock module. The RTC ensures accurate timekeeping even during power outages due to its dedicated backup battery.

Automatic Time Synchronization

Whenever Wi-Fi connectivity is available, the ESP32 synchronizes the RTC with Network Time Protocol (NTP) servers, ensuring long-term time accuracy without manual intervention.

Cloud Integration

Attendance records are automatically uploaded to a Google Apps Script backend through secure HTTPS communication. This enables centralized attendance monitoring and remote record management.

Dual Backup Architecture

To maximize data reliability, attendance logs are stored in:

ESP32 LittleFS Flash Storage
SD Card Storage

This dual-layer storage architecture ensures attendance data remains protected under various failure conditions.

Smart Wi-Fi Management

The system continuously monitors network connectivity and automatically reconnects whenever a connection is lost. Wi-Fi credentials can be configured remotely through serial commands.

OLED User Interface

A 128×64 SSD1306 OLED display provides visual feedback regarding:

Device status
SD card health
System startup
User interactions
Connectivity information
Administrative Control System

Administrators can manage users, view logs, reset components, configure Wi-Fi, and perform maintenance operations through a serial command interface.

Self-Diagnostic Capabilities

The device automatically verifies the operational status of:

Fingerprint sensor
RTC module
SD card
Wi-Fi connection
Cloud synchronization service

This allows rapid troubleshooting and reliable deployment in real-world environments.

System Architecture

The project follows a modular architecture where each subsystem operates independently while collaborating with others.

The fingerprint sensor performs user identification, the RTC provides accurate timestamps, storage modules handle local backups, Wi-Fi modules manage connectivity, and a background FreeRTOS task handles cloud synchronization.

This architecture ensures that attendance marking remains functional even if one subsystem temporarily fails.

